The active stone (or, specifically, the active square medium-blue stone, since that is the only one shown in the test phase) causes one, and possibly two changes in the inactive stone:  (1) the inactive stone gains one extra edge or side (e.g. a triangle is transformed into a square, a pentagon into a hexgon, a hexagon into a heptagon, etc.); this change always happens  (2) the inactive stone has its color changed to a dark blue (darker than the blue of the active stone); however, if the inactive stone was already that color, its color is not changed
feedback: Although I said no to the question about whether my impression of how the active stones worked changed at the end of the 18 trials, obviously I had to extend the idea I proposed after the learning phase, since, in the learning phase only medium-blue square active stones were ever shown. Since there was no real evidence to go on, I was technically just guessing, but I guessed consistently according to the following idea:  (1) the active stone caused the inactive stone's color to change to the color one shade darker than the active stone (e.g. a medium active stone caused the inactive stone to become dark; a dark active stone caused the inactive stone to become very dark); if the inactive stone was already of that color, its color was not changed  (2) the active stone caused the inactive stone to gain N-3 sides/edges, where N = the number of sides/edges that the active stone had; hence, a triangular active stone did not cause the inactive stone's shape to change; a square active stone caused the inactive stone to gain 1 side/edge; a pentagonal active stone caused the inactive stone to gain 2 sides/edges; etc.
